{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500134"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:09:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:09:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1612"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1612"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.77,0.03,0.08,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1612"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114585"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1612"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1612"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96588"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35504"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42352"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48120"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114585"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a 12-hour history of dull central chest pain. He had a respiratory tract infection two weeks ago. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He is a non-smoker, drinks alcohol socially, and denies recreational drug use. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary embolism","Pericarditis","Hyperkalaemia","Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome","Myocardial infarction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chest pain following a recent viral infection, with ECG changes characteristic of acute pericarditis. The ECG in the first two weeks of pericarditis typically shows widespread concave ST elevation and PR depression throughout most of the limb leads (I, II, III, aVL, aVF) and precordial leads (V2-6), with reciprocal ST depression and PR elevation in lead aVR (and sometimes V1). Sinus tachycardia is also common due to pain and/or pericardial effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct diagnosis. The recent respiratory tract infection is a common precipitant, and the ECG findings are pathognomonic. Treatment typically involves colchicine and/or non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs such as aspirin or ibuprofen. Troponin, serial ECGs and transthoracic echocardiography should be performed to exclude myocarditis and acute coronary syndrome, as well as potential complications such as pericardial effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options can be distinguished by their characteristic presentations:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E: Typically presents with pleuritic chest pain and dyspnoea, with ECG showing sinus tachycardia, right axis deviation, or the classic S1Q3T3 pattern. Risk factors include immobilisation, recent surgery, or thrombophilia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E: Causes peaked T waves, prolonged PR interval, widened QRS complex, and eventually sine wave pattern in severe cases.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWolff-Parkinson-White syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E: Characterised by short PR interval, delta wave (slurred upstroke of QRS complex), and widened QRS complex. Usually presents with palpitations rather than chest pain.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E: Shows ST elevation in a specific coronary territory rather than widespread, with reciprocal ST depression in opposite leads. Would be unusual in a 25-year-old without risk factors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pericarditis presents with widespread concave ST elevation and PR depression in most leads, with reciprocal changes in aVR.","Recent viral infection is a common precipitant of acute pericarditis in young adults."],"references":["McNamara N, Ibrahim A, Satti Z, et al. Acute pericarditis: a review of current diagnostic and management guidelines. Future Cardiol. 2019;15(2):119-126."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96588"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1612"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21902"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21902"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/beyjuNw5DXBxY84NwS6vPUfcbv49M5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/beyjuNw5DXBxY84NwS6vPUfcbv49M5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":315}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96588"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T20:35:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-